{"parentUuid":"2d579849-97f6-4a1b-961d-4156b276d400","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9fbbbe5896b1a951","attachment":{"type":"skill_listing","content":"- api-edge-conventions: Request-lifecycle hardening for an HTTP surface — rate limiting/throttling, CORS, security headers, the error-envelope facade, idempotency keys, and outbound timeouts/retries. The implementation counterpart to STRIDE's DoS/Tampering threats. Invoke when a feature exposes or consumes an HTTP surface.\n- auth-patterns: Firebase-default auth facade, OAuth 2.0 provider setup, the two Duo MFA paths, the mfa_verified custom-claim contract, and the require_auth/require_mfa/require_role guard pattern. Invoke when a feature touches identity or protected resources.\n- ci-conventions: The per-project CI merge gate (pipeline-ci.yml) — what each job re-verifies and what it can't, the SCAN_BASE re-run contract, the CI waiver channel, the branch-protection checklist, and how deploy workflows chain on. Invoke when a project has or needs GitHub Actions CI.\n- code-standards: Naming, function size, comment/docstring rules, SOLID, facade modules, and security invariants (no hardcoded secrets, row-level security, input validation/output encoding) — the implementation agent's one coding-standards reference.\n- containerization-conventions: When containerizing (Docker) an application is good practice vs. running it as a direct process or serverless function — the decision rubric, the Kubernetes-vs-managed-runtime call, Dockerfile/image conventions, and threat-model touchpoints. Invoke from planning whenever the runtime/packaging of the app is in question.\n- dast-conventions: The runtime DAST axis (dast-plan.md) — what each layer guarantees, the dast.env/dast-budget.json opt-in mechanics, the DAST-readiness acceptance criteria planning must emit for an HTTP surface (served OpenAPI schema, seeded test user, auth context), and the tuning/false-positive protocol. Invoke when a feature exposes an HTTP surface the running app will serve.\n- data-protection-conventions: Data-classification taxonomy and the required at-rest protection control per class (credential → slow KDF; sensitive/regulated PII → KMS envelope field-encryption; personal → SSE; non-sensitive → none), plus the crypto-facade rule and the KMS key-access pattern. Invoke when a feature STORES user data — planning classifies each stored field, implementation builds the control through one facade, security reconciles implemented vs declared. Implements the verifiable side of ASVS V14/V11.4.2.\n- ddia-patterns: Condensed decision guide from Designing Data-Intensive Applications — storage-model, replication, partitioning, and consistency trade-offs to weigh when a plan adds or changes storage or messaging.\n- debugging-escalation-protocol: Retry caps, the sanity-vs-remediation role split, cap-out reporting, and when to escalate to planning versus patch in place for the debugging agent.\n- delivery-conventions: Build/tag/sign/provenance rules for the post-merge artifact path (build-provenance.yml) — immutable SHA tags, cosign keyless signing, SBOM + SLSA attestation, verify-before-rollout, container hardening, and continuous vulnerability re-scanning. Invoke when the change ships a container image or touches a deploy workflow.\n- dependency-audit-policy: plan-audit's dependency reality-check (anti-slopsquatting registry lookup) + version policy (cooldown, obsolescence, exact-pin determinism, architectural fit). Invoked only when the plan introduces a new third-party dependency.\n- deployment-checklist-and-rollback: Pre-flight gate checks, the commit-then-push-then-PR GitHub handoff sequence, and a pointer to CI for production delivery and rollback.\n- diff-scoping-conventions: Shared working-tree change-set logic so security and testing scope to the same files, plus the change-set hash that testing records as tested_change_hash and documentation records as reviewed_change_hash.\n- doc-conventions: Directory/root README structure, what belongs in system_architecture.md, the allowed Mermaid diagram types, and the incremental-update plus PR-description rules — the documentation agent's one reference.\n- frontend-design: Guidance for distinctive, intentional visual design when building new UI or reshaping an existing one. Helps with aesthetic direction, typography, and making choices that don't read as templated defaults.\n- iac-conventions: Terraform infra/ facade layout, AWS provider + S3/DynamoDB remote state, GitHub OIDC role assumption, tagging/naming, and the IaC security baseline. Invoke only when the change provisions cloud resources (an infra/ directory).\n- logging-conventions: Standard structured-log field set, PII redaction rules, log-level semantics, the structlog (Python, default) / Pino (JS) logger facade, OTel trace-ID propagation, and the AWS CloudWatch/X-Ray backend. Invoke when a feature produces observable events.\n- observability-conventions: Operational observability wiring for a deployed app — Sentry error tracking (release-tagged), OTel→CloudWatch/X-Ray export, SLO definitions + burn-rate alarms (the signal the canary rollback consumes), synthetic monitoring, mobile crash reporting (dSYM/source-map upload), and the read-only triage feedback loop. Invoke when a change ships to a real environment or defines SLOs. Distinct from logging-conventions (app-side log format/PII/trace-IDs), which it builds on.\n- pipeline-orchestration: Stage order, the .pipeline/* interlock-file contracts, gate semantics, and the fresh-context handoff rule for whoever drives the multi-agent SDLC pipeline.\n- requirements-elicitation: Operator-invoked, human-facing interrogation that sharpens a feature brief BEFORE planning — a relentless interview that surfaces the edge cases, state transitions, failure behavior, and non-functional budgets a one-line request leaves implicit. Produces .pipeline/requirements.md (resolved / open / out-of-scope). Use at the very start of a feature, before design-spec/planning, when the brief is thin or ambiguous. Never auto-invoked; the operator runs it and answers the questions.\n- secrets-management: Runtime secrets pattern — fetch from AWS Secrets Manager / SSM Parameter Store behind a client facade, caching + rotation, no secrets in env files/images/tfvars, and the redaction tie-in. Invoke when a feature consumes a credential (API key, DB password, token) at runtime.\n- skill-creator: Create new skills, modify and improve existing skills, and measure skill performance. Use when users want to create a skill from scratch, edit, or optimize an existing skill, run evals to test a skill, benchmark skill performance with variance analysis, or optimize a skill's description for better triggering accuracy.\n- stride-threat-model-template: STRIDE worksheet — trust boundaries, per-category threat prompts, and the severity rubric appended to plan.md.\n- triage-conventions: The incident-brief schema, the redaction rule, the provenance + injection-report format, and the read-only Sentry MCP setup/scope checklist for the triage agent. Invoke at the start of every triage run.\n- app-store-submission-requirements: App Store submission requirements made accountable — privacy manifest & nutrition labels, permission usage strings, code signing/capabilities, common Review Guideline rejection causes, and the acceptance criteria planning must emit so these are caught early, not at upload.\n- apple-hig-compliance: Apple Human Interface Guidelines conformance for iOS — native navigation, layout & safe areas, touch targets, SF Symbols, Dynamic Type, dark mode, motion/haptics, and the checklist for mapping a web design's idioms onto iOS-native patterns.\n- ast-grep-rules: Structural (AST) search rules the security agent can run with ast-grep to catch syntax-shaped defects that regex/Semgrep miss, plus the advisory-only contract (findings inform the report, never the deterministic counts).\n- claude-design-to-swiftui: Digest a Claude Design (or any HTML/CSS/JS) export and replicate it faithfully in idiomatic SwiftUI — token extraction, the full CSS→modifier map, layout translation, fidelity verification, and the web idioms that have no native equivalent.\n- design-system-conventions: The normalization taxonomy for turning an untrusted design bundle (Claude Design / Figma export / screenshots, or a Figma MCP pull) into a reviewable .pipeline/design-spec.md — screen/flow inventory, component inventory, design-token table, layout intent, interaction notes, the required \"needs native mapping\" section, and the provenance + injection report. Platform-agnostic (feeds both a web and a native-iOS plan).\n- google-play-submission-requirements: Google Play submission requirements made accountable — the Data safety form, target-SDK policy, permission declarations, in-app account deletion (incl. the web path), Play Billing, common rejection causes, and the acceptance criteria planning must emit so these are caught early, not at upload.\n- semgrep-ruleset-guide: Which Semgrep configs apply to this project's stack, the severity to critical/warning mapping, and how findings roll into security-report.md counts.\n- swift-conventions: Production Swift/SwiftUI conventions — architecture (MV with @Observable), state, navigation, Swift 6 concurrency, data layer, dependency injection, error handling, performance, accessibility, project layout, and the testing stack. The Swift counterpart to code-standards.\n- test-conventions: Project test layout, mocking strategy, unit-vs-integration boundary, runner and coverage commands, and coverage thresholds.\n- dataviz: Use this skill whenever you are about to create ANY chart, graph, plot, dashboard, or data visualization, in ANY output medium — an HTML or React artifact, inline SVG, plotting code in any library (matplotlib, plotly, d3, Recharts, …), an image/PNG you will render and upload, or a chart shared into Slack. Read it BEFORE writing the first line of chart code, choosing chart colors, building a stat tile / meter / KPI row, or laying out a dashboard. Produces visualizations that read as one system — elegant, accessible, consistent in light and dark — using a brand-neutral placeholder palette you swap for your own. Teaches a design-system-agnostic method: a form heuristic, a color formula with a runnable validator, mark specs, and interaction rules. A validated default palette is documented in `references/palette.md` — swap that file's values for your brand's. Triggers on: \"chart\", \"graph\", \"plot\", \"data viz\", \"visualization\", \"dashboard\", \"analytics\", \"visualize data\", \"categorical colors\", \"sequential / diverging palette\", \"stat tile\", \"sparkline\", \"heatmap\", \"legend\", \"axis\", \"tooltip\", \"chart colors\", \"color by series\".\n- artifact-design: Design guidance and fundamentals for Artifacts.\n- update-config: Use this skill to configure the Claude Code harness via settings.json. Automated behaviors (\"from now on when X\", \"each time X\", \"whenever X\", \"before/after X\") require hooks configured in settings.json - the harness executes these, not Claude, so memory/preferences cannot fulfill them. Also use for: permissions (\"allow X\", \"add permission\", \"move permission to\"), env vars (\"set X=Y\"), hook troubleshooting, or any changes to settings.json/settings.local.json files. Examples: \"allow npm commands\", \"add bq permission to global settings\", \"move permission to user settings\", \"set DEBUG=true\", \"when claude stops show X\". For simple settings like theme/model, suggest the /config command.\n- keybindings-help: Use when the user wants to customize keyboard shortcuts, rebind keys, add chord bindings, or modify ~/.claude/keybindings.json. Examples: \"rebind ctrl+s\", \"add a chord shortcut\", \"change the submit key\", \"customize keybindings\".\n- verify: Verify that a code change actually does what it's supposed to by exercising it end-to-end and observing behavior — drive the affected flow, not just tests or typecheck. Run before committing nontrivial changes; bootstraps this repo's project verify skill if none exists yet. Don't invoke it on a diff that only touches tests, docs, or other code with no runtime surface to drive (a change to product source always has one) — there's nothing to observe.\n- code-review: Review the current diff for correctness bugs and reuse/simplification/efficiency cleanups at the given effort level (low/medium: fewer, high-confidence findings; high→max: broader coverage, may include uncertain findings; ultra: deep multi-agent review in the cloud). Pass --comment to post findings as inline PR comments, or --fix to apply the findings to the working tree after the review.\n- simplify: Review the changed code for reuse, simplification, efficiency, and altitude cleanups, then apply the fixes. Quality only — it does not hunt for bugs; use /code-review for that.\n- fewer-permission-prompts: Scan your transcripts for common read-only Bash and MCP tool calls, then add a prioritized allowlist to project .claude/settings.json to reduce permission prompts.\n- loop: Run a prompt or slash command on a recurring interval (e.g. /loop 5m /foo). Omit the interval to let the model self-pace. - When the user wants to set up a recurring task, poll for status, or run something repeatedly on an interval (e.g. \"check the deploy every 5 minutes\", \"keep running /babysit-prs\"). Do NOT invoke for one-off tasks.\n- schedule: Create, update, list, or run scheduled cloud agents (routines) that execute on a cron schedule. - When the user wants to schedule a recurring cloud agent, set up automated tasks, create a cron job for Claude Code, or manage their scheduled agents/routines. Also use when the user wants a one-time scheduled run (\"run this once at 3pm\", \"remind me to check X tomorrow\").\n- claude-api: Reference for the Claude API / Anthropic SDK — model ids, pricing, params, streaming, tool use, MCP, agents, caching, token counting, model migration.\nTRIGGER — read BEFORE opening the target file; don't skip because it \"looks like a one-liner\" — whenever: the prompt names Claude/Anthropic in any form (Claude, Anthropic, Fable, Opus, Sonnet, Haiku, `anthropic`, `@anthropic-ai`, `claude-*`, `us.anthropic.*`, `[1m]`); the user asks about an LLM (pricing/model choice/limits/caching) — never answer from memory; OR the task is LLM-shaped with provider unstated (agent/MCP/tool-definition/multi-agent/RAG/LLM-judge/computer-use; generate/summarize/extract/classify/rewrite/converse over NL; debugging refusals/cutoffs/streaming/tool-calls/tokens).\nSKIP only when another provider is being worked on (overrides all triggers): OpenAI/GPT/Gemini/Llama/Mistral/Cohere/Ollama named in the query; OR `grep -rE 'openai|langchain_openai|google.generativeai|genai|mistralai|cohere|ollama'` over the project hits (run this grep FIRST if no provider named — don't Read the file).\n- run: Launch and drive this project's app to see a change working. Use when asked to run, start, or screenshot the app, or to confirm a change works in the real app (not just tests). First looks for a project skill that already covers launching the app; otherwise falls back to built-in patterns per project type (CLI, server, TUI, Electron, browser-driven, library).\n- init: Initialize a new CLAUDE.md file with codebase documentation\n- review: Review a GitHub pull request; for your working diff use /code-review\n- security-review: Complete a security review of the pending changes on the current branch","skillCount":48,"isInitial":true,"names":["api-edge-conventions","auth-patterns","ci-conventions","code-standards","containerization-conventions","dast-conventions","data-protection-conventions","ddia-patterns","debugging-escalation-protocol","delivery-conventions","dependency-audit-policy","deployment-checklist-and-rollback","diff-scoping-conventions","doc-conventions","frontend-design","iac-conventions","logging-conventions","observability-conventions","pipeline-orchestration","requirements-elicitation","secrets-management","skill-creator","stride-threat-model-template","triage-conventions","app-store-submission-requirements","apple-hig-compliance","ast-grep-rules","claude-design-to-swiftui","design-system-conventions","google-play-submission-requirements","semgrep-ruleset-guide","swift-conventions","test-conventions","dataviz","artifact-design","update-config","keybindings-help","verify","code-review","simplify","fewer-permission-prompts","loop","schedule","claude-api","run","init","review","security-review"]},"type":"attachment","uuid":"3afb4a28-13d0-43df-9dea-1b84fd5c2770","timestamp":"2026-07-09T01:03:52.831Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
