{"parentUuid":"fea6ba95-9f52-4962-bc0a-a4816fabb86f","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9fbbbe5896b1a951","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccqb3PQHzM1EDcoRmViXW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011AaxCj2Ga7Ks1q7LWQ9USR","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\tests\\integration\\test_quota_migration.py"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5278,"cache_read_input_tokens":73882,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5278,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccqb3NS1CmPYDdWctqnw5","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"a23a02bf-f3d5-473c-8cb0-15e4488eb35b","timestamp":"2026-07-09T01:07:33.132Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"a23a02bf-f3d5-473c-8cb0-15e4488eb35b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"bcf5258e-2708-4b49-a1f7-27fad0c3c471","agentId":"a9fbbbe5896b1a951","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011AaxCj2Ga7Ks1q7LWQ9USR","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"AC16: migration `0003` (quotas table + `api_keys.scope` column) round-trips\n2\t`up -> down -> 0002 -> up` and re-enforces every constraint identically.\n3\t\n4\t`quotas` is a create-migration (its `down` drops the table — row survival\n5\tacross `down` is undefined by definition, only schema + constraints are\n6\tasserted). `api_keys.scope` is an add-column on a populated table — its\n7\tpre-existing rows (and their other columns) must survive the round-trip; the\n8\t`scope` value itself is expected to reset to the `'ingest'` default on `down`\n9\t(the defined expand/contract contract of an add-column), not a data-loss bug.\n10\t\n11\tUses its own scratch Postgres testcontainer (module-scoped), independent of\n12\tthe shared session-scoped `postgres_url` fixture in `tests/integration/conftest.py`,\n13\tsince this test owns the migration lifecycle itself (down to 0002, back to head).\n14\t\"\"\"\n15\t\n16\timport subprocess\n17\timport sys\n18\tfrom pathlib import Path\n19\t\n20\timport pytest\n21\tfrom sqlalchemy import text\n22\tfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import create_async_engine\n23\tfrom testcontainers.postgres import PostgresContainer\n24\t\n25\t_REPO_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parents[2]\n26\t\n27\t\n28\tdef _asyncpg_url(sync_url: str) -> str:\n29\t    \"\"\"Convert testcontainers' default `postgresql+psycopg2://` URL to the\n30\t    `postgresql+asyncpg://` dialect the application (and Alembic's env.py) uses.\"\"\"\n31\t    return sync_url.replace(\"postgresql+psycopg2://\", \"postgresql+asyncpg://\")\n32\t\n33\t\n34\tdef _run_alembic(*args: str, env: dict) -> None:\n35\t    \"\"\"Run `alembic <args>` out-of-process against `env`'s `DATABASE_URL`,\n36\t    failing loudly with the captured output if the migration itself fails.\"\"\"\n37\t    result = subprocess.run(\n38\t        [sys.executable, \"-m\", \"alembic\", *args],\n39\t        cwd=str(_REPO_ROOT),\n40\t        env=env,\n41\t        capture_output=True,\n42\t        text=True,\n43\t    )\n44\t    assert result.returncode == 0, f\"alembic {' '.join(args)} failed:\\n{result.stdout}\\n{result.stderr}\"\n45\t\n46\t\n47\t@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n48\tdef migration_env():\n49\t    \"\"\"A scratch Postgres this test owns end to end (migrated up/down/up\n50\t    repeatedly), independent of the shared session-scoped container.\"\"\"\n51\t    import os\n52\t\n53\t    with PostgresContainer(\"postgres:16-alpine\") as postgres:\n54\t        url = _asyncpg_url(postgres.get_connection_url())\n55\t        env = dict(os.environ)\n56\t        env[\"DATABASE_URL\"] = url\n57\t        yield env, url\n58\t\n59\t\n60\tasync def _seed_api_key(url: str, *, key_id: str, scope: str | None = None) -> int:\n61\t    \"\"\"Insert one `api_keys` row (optionally with an explicit `scope`) and\n62\t    return its surrogate id.\"\"\"\n63\t    engine = create_async_engine(url)\n64\t    columns = \"key_id, secret_hash, label, rate_limit_per_sec\"\n65\t    values = \":key_id, :hash, :label, :rate\"\n66\t    params = {\"key_id\": key_id, \"hash\": f\"$argon2id$fake${key_id}\", \"label\": key_id, \"rate\": 100}\n67\t    if scope is not None:\n68\t        columns += \", scope\"\n69\t        values += \", :scope\"\n70\t        params[\"scope\"] = scope\n71\t    async with engine.begin() as connection:\n72\t        result = await connection.execute(\n73\t            text(f\"INSERT INTO api_keys ({columns}) VALUES ({values}) RETURNING id\"), params\n74\t        )\n75\t        api_key_id = result.scalar_one()\n76\t    await engine.dispose()\n77\t    return api_key_id\n78\t\n79\t\n80\tasync def _fetch_api_key_row(url: str, api_key_id: int) -> dict:\n81\t    engine = create_async_engine(url)\n82\t    async with engine.connect() as connection:\n83\t        row = (\n84\t            await connection.execute(\n85\t                text(\"SELECT id, key_id, secret_hash, label, rate_limit_per_sec, scope FROM api_keys WHERE id = :id\"),\n86\t                {\"id\": api_key_id},\n87\t            )\n88\t        ).mappings().first()\n89\t    await engine.dispose()\n90\t    return dict(row)\n91\t\n92\t\n93\tasync def test_0003_roundtrip_schema_and_constraints(migration_env):\n94\t    \"\"\"AC16: `0003` up -> down (to 0002) -> up restores the `quotas` schema and\n95\t    re-enforces its PK/FK/CHECK, restores the `api_keys.scope` CHECK, and\n96\t    leaves pre-existing `api_keys` rows (other than `scope`, which resets to\n97\t    its default) intact.\"\"\"\n98\t    env, url = migration_env\n99\t\n100\t    _run_alembic(\"upgrade\", \"head\", env=env)\n101\t\n102\t    admin_key_id = await _seed_api_key(url, key_id=\"admin-key\", scope=\"admin\")\n103\t    ingest_key_id = await _seed_api_key(url, key_id=\"ingest-key\")  # default scope\n104\t\n105\t    engine = create_async_engine(url)\n106\t    async with engine.begin() as connection:\n107\t        await connection.execute(\n108\t            text(\n109\t                \"INSERT INTO quotas (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window) \"\n110\t                \"VALUES (:id, 'cust_1', 'api_calls', 1000)\"\n111\t            ),\n112\t            {\"id\": admin_key_id},\n113\t        )\n114\t    await engine.dispose()\n115\t\n116\t    _run_alembic(\"downgrade\", \"0002\", env=env)\n117\t\n118\t    # `quotas` must be gone entirely after downgrade (create-migration: schema\n119\t    # rollback only, row survival across `down` is not asserted).\n120\t    engine = create_async_engine(url)\n121\t    async with engine.connect() as connection:\n122\t        table_exists = (\n123\t            await connection.execute(\n124\t                text(\"SELECT to_regclass('public.quotas') IS NOT NULL\")\n125\t            )\n126\t        ).scalar_one()\n127\t    await engine.dispose()\n128\t    assert table_exists is False, \"quotas must not exist after downgrading past 0003\"\n129\t\n130\t    # The pre-existing api_keys rows must survive the column drop (only the\n131\t    # `scope` column itself disappears — the rows are untouched otherwise).\n132\t    engine = create_async_engine(url)\n133\t    async with engine.connect() as connection:\n134\t        surviving_count = (\n135\t            await connection.execute(text(\"SELECT COUNT(*) FROM api_keys\"))\n136\t        ).scalar_one()\n137\t        has_scope_column = (\n138\t            await connection.execute(\n139\t                text(\n140\t                    \"SELECT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.columns \"\n141\t                    \"WHERE table_name = 'api_keys' AND column_name = 'scope')\"\n142\t                )\n143\t            )\n144\t        ).scalar_one()\n145\t    await engine.dispose()\n146\t    assert surviving_count == 2, \"the two pre-existing api_keys rows must survive the downgrade\"\n147\t    assert has_scope_column is False, \"the scope column itself must be dropped on downgrade\"\n148\t\n149\t    _run_alembic(\"upgrade\", \"head\", env=env)\n150\t\n151\t    # Re-enforce: PK (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) rejects a duplicate.\n152\t    engine = create_async_engine(url)\n153\t    async with engine.begin() as connection:\n154\t        await connection.execute(\n155\t            text(\n156\t                \"INSERT INTO quotas (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window) \"\n157\t                \"VALUES (:id, 'cust_1', 'api_calls', 500)\"\n158\t            ),\n159\t            {\"id\": admin_key_id},\n160\t        )\n161\t        with pytest.raises(Exception):\n162\t            async with connection.begin_nested():\n163\t                await connection.execute(\n164\t                    text(\n165\t                        \"INSERT INTO quotas (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window) \"\n166\t                        \"VALUES (:id, 'cust_1', 'api_calls', 999)\"\n167\t                    ),\n168\t                    {\"id\": admin_key_id},\n169\t                )\n170\t\n171\t        # FK: api_key_id must reference an existing api_keys row.\n172\t        with pytest.raises(Exception):\n173\t            async with connection.begin_nested():\n174\t                await connection.execute(\n175\t                    text(\n176\t                        \"INSERT INTO quotas (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window) \"\n177\t                        \"VALUES (999999, 'cust_2', 'api_calls', 100)\"\n178\t                    )\n179\t                )\n180\t\n181\t        # CHECK (limit_per_window >= 1): zero and negative are rejected.\n182\t        with pytest.raises(Exception):\n183\t            async with connection.begin_nested():\n184\t                await connection.execute(\n185\t                    text(\n186\t                        \"INSERT INTO quotas (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window) \"\n187\t                        \"VALUES (:id, 'cust_3', 'api_calls', 0)\"\n188\t                    ),\n189\t                    {\"id\": admin_key_id},\n190\t                )\n191\t        with pytest.raises(Exception):\n192\t            async with connection.begin_nested():\n193\t                await connection.execute(\n194\t                    text(\n195\t                        \"INSERT INTO quotas (api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window) \"\n196\t                        \"VALUES (:id, 'cust_4', 'api_calls', -5)\"\n197\t                    ),\n198\t                    {\"id\": admin_key_id},\n199\t                )\n200\t\n201\t        # api_keys.scope CHECK IN ('ingest', 'admin') must still be enforced.\n202\t        with pytest.raises(Exception):\n203\t            async with connection.begin_nested():\n204\t                await connection.execute(\n205\t                    text(\n206\t                        \"INSERT INTO api_keys (key_id, secret_hash, label, rate_limit_per_sec, scope) \"\n207\t                        \"VALUES ('bad-scope-key', '$argon2id$x', 'bad', 100, 'superuser')\"\n208\t                    )\n209\t                )\n210\t    await engine.dispose()\n211\t\n212\t    # The pre-existing rows survive the full round-trip; scope resets to the\n213\t    # 'ingest' default (the defined expand/contract behavior of an add-column,\n214\t    # not data loss of a populated business column).\n215\t    admin_row = await _fetch_api_key_row(url, admin_key_id)\n216\t    ingest_row = await _fetch_api_key_row(url, ingest_key_id)\n217\t    assert admin_row[\"key_id\"] == \"admin-key\"\n218\t    assert admin_row[\"scope\"] == \"ingest\", \"scope resets to the column default after down->up, per plan\"\n219\t    assert ingest_row[\"key_id\"] == \"ingest-key\"\n220\t    assert ingest_row[\"scope\"] == \"ingest\"\n221\t\n222\t    # Leave the schema at head for any subsequent module-scoped use.\n223\t    _run_alembic(\"upgrade\", \"head\", env=env)\n224\t"}]},"uuid":"0f6832ae-bf68-46ee-aa81-1dd5ad63c10b","timestamp":"2026-07-09T01:07:33.151Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a23a02bf-f3d5-473c-8cb0-15e4488eb35b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"0f6832ae-bf68-46ee-aa81-1dd5ad63c10b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9fbbbe5896b1a951","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccqb664qpcP6HiWZps6Xc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5672,"cache_read_input_tokens":79160,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5672,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccqb64mTNEbkvYQRSZRNE","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"f8a7b126-fb20-4bf4-abc5-43b5eec75918","timestamp":"2026-07-09T01:08:15.086Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"f8a7b126-fb20-4bf4-abc5-43b5eec75918","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9fbbbe5896b1a951","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccqb664qpcP6HiWZps6Xc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I've completed a full cross-file trace of the metric-quotas data path. The call sites are all consistent (no broken signatures), the lock ordering is uniform (event-row → `quotas` `FOR UPDATE` → `usage_rollup` upsert on every path, so no cross-table deadlock), the migration constraints match the repo assumptions (PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`, `ON CONFLICT` target matches; `CHECK limit>=1` matches `conint(ge=1)`; scope CHECK matches), the error handler forwards the `Retry-After` header, and the quota check reads `usage_rollup` under the same `api_key_id` the write path uses. The design is careful. The candidate findings below are the defensible ones.\n\n---\n\n**Candidate 1 — quota enforcement is silently bypassed when a tenant uses a separate ingest key**\n- file: `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`\n- line: 121 (the `WHERE api_key_id = :api_key_id` lookup; enforcement in `src/services/events_service.py:98`, quota write in `src/services/quota_service.py:40`)\n- summary: Quotas are keyed by `api_key_id`, so a cap written by an admin key is only enforced on events ingested under that *same* key; ingesting under any other key of the same operator reads no quota row and is treated as unlimited.\n- failure_scenario: An operator has a pre-existing `scope='ingest'` key K1 (already used by their `POST /v1/events` clients) and provisions a new `scope='admin'` key K2 to call `PUT /v1/quotas {customer_id=c, metric=m, limit=10}`. The quota row is stored under K2's `api_key_id`. Clients keep ingesting with K1, so `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(api_key_id=K1...)` matches zero rows, returns `None`, and every event is admitted — usage grows unbounded past 10 with no 429 ever returned. Nothing in the code or schema forces the \"use one key for both\" rule the docs assume.\n\n**Candidate 2 — strict enforcement silently depends on READ COMMITTED isolation not being changed**\n- file: `src/db/session.py`\n- line: 31 (`create_async_engine(...)` sets no `isolation_level`); relied on at `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py:131`\n- summary: The two-statement lock-then-read cap mechanism is correct only under READ COMMITTED (each statement gets a fresh snapshot); the engine relies on that being the unpinned Postgres default rather than asserting it.\n- failure_scenario: If the engine is ever configured with `isolation_level=\"REPEATABLE READ\"` (or a role/DB default sets it), a waiter that blocked on the `FOR UPDATE` quota lock unblocks after the holder commits but then reads `usage_rollup` from its transaction's *original* snapshot (taken before the wait), sees the stale pre-increment total, and admits an event that pushes usage past `L` — the exact TOCTOU the design claims to prevent, now failing under concurrency with no test signal because the perf/concurrency tests run on the default isolation. This is a latent fragility, not a defect in the current diff.\n\nI did not find a correctness defect in the current logic itself (concurrency serialization, rollback-on-reject, idempotency-replay skipping the quota check, `R+Q>L` boundary reaching exactly `L`, `Retry-After` header propagation, and the migration round-trip are all correct as written). Candidate 1 is the strongest real-world hazard; Candidate 2 is a robustness note."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5672,"cache_read_input_tokens":79160,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5672,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccqb64mTNEbkvYQRSZRNE","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"5e51b9cd-091b-414e-b6a7-b4e487a5c69f","timestamp":"2026-07-09T01:08:31.701Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
